04431nam a22006255i 9780520972636DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20202020cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209726367 a10.1525/97805209726362doi  a(DE-B1597)551362  a(OCoLC)1124796973  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aBL1812.T26b.N4 2020 7aSOC0020002bisacsh04a299.512231 aNg, Emily, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Time of Lost Gods :bMediumship, Madness, and the Ghost after Mao /cEmily Ng. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPrologue: We Never Should Have Met -- tIntroduction: The China of China -- t1. After the Storm -- t2. Ten Thousand Years -- t3. Spectral Collision -- t4. A Soul Adrift -- t5. Vertiginous Abbreviation -- tCoda: Those Who Remain -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTraversing visible and invisible realms, A Time of Lost Gods attends to profound rereadings of politics, religion, and madness in the cosmic accounts of spirit mediumship. Drawing on research across a temple, a psychiatric unit, and the home altars of spirit mediums in a rural county of China’s Central Plain, it asks: What ghostly forms emerge after the death of Mao and the so-called end of history? The story of religion in China since the market reforms of the late 1970s is often told through its destruction under Mao and relative flourishing thereafter. Here, those who engage in mediumship offer a different history of the present. They approach Mao’s reign not simply as an earthly secular rule, but an exceptional interval of divine sovereignty, after which the cosmos collapsed into chaos. Caught between a fading era and an ever-receding horizon, those “left behind” by labor outmigration refigure the evacuated hometown as an ethical-spiritual center to come, amidst a proliferation of madness-inducing spirits. Following pronouncements of China’s rise, and in the wake of what Chinese intellectuals termed semicolonialism, the stories here tell of spirit mediums, patients, and psychiatrists caught in a shared dilemma, in a time when gods have lost their way.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGhosts. 0aMental illnesszChinazHenan Sheng. 0aTang-ki worshipzChinazHenan Sheng. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070472308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology, Education, Psychology 2020z9783110704549oZDB-23-SEW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069041540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520972636?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520972636423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520972636/original  a978-3-11-069041-5  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-070472-3  EBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishb2020  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGGb2020  aZDB-23-SEWb2020